== Overview == {{seealso|Kijishi}} Ogura Shō in Aichi District, Shiga Prefecture, is considered the birthplace of {{ill|Kijishi|ja|木地師|12=draft|12=draft}}. In the late Edo period, the {{ill|Shirakawa family|ja|白川伯王家|12=draft|12=draft}} of the {{ill|Jingikan|ja|神祗官|1=Department of Divinities|2=ja|3=神祇官|12=draft|12=draft}} oversaw the {{ill|Ōkimi kijiso-jinja|ja|大皇器地祖神社|12=draft|12=draft}} (also known as Daitakami or Kyōji) in {{ill|Kimi no Hatamura|ja|君ガ畑村|12=draft|12=draft}} (modern-day {{ill|Kimi no Hatamachi, Higashiōmi|ja|東近江市君ヶ畑町|12=draft|12=draft}}). Similarly, the {{ill|Yoshida family|ja|吉田家|12=draft|12=draft}}, also of the Jingikan, oversaw {{ill|Tsutsui Shrine|ja|筒井神社|12=draft|12=draft}} (also known as Tsutsui Hachiman or Kaeriumian) in {{ill|Hirugai Village|ja|蛭谷村|12=draft|12=draft}} (modern-day {{ill|Hirugai Town, Higashiōmi|ja|東近江市蛭谷町|12=draft|12=draft}}). Both shrines enshrined the spirit of {{ill|Prince Koretaka|ja|惟喬親王|12=draft|12=draft}}, who was believed to be the ancestral deity of the Kijishi, and proclaimed this widely.
At the time, Kijishi were dispersed across the country, sometimes practicing their trade with permission from the {{ill|Imperial Court|ja|朝廷|12=draft|12=draft}} or the {{ill|Edo shogunate|ja|Tokugawa shogunate|12=draft|12=draft}}. Bringing these scattered Kijishi under the influence of their respective shrines would yield significant income for the shrines.
Thus, the Shirakawa and Yoshida families sought out these Kijishi, claiming their shrines to be the legitimate spiritual sites of Prince Koretaka. They forcibly registered Kijishi as ujiko and sometimes issued forged documents to assert their authority. This competition for control often led to disputes between the two shrines.
As a result, the Kijishi were registered with either shrine, paid monetary contributions, and assumed certain obligations. The shrines also wielded their authority to grant or deny business licenses to the Kijishi. While it remains unclear whether Prince Koretaka was truly their ancestor, the Kijishi came to believe he was their occupational founder due to these events.
The scale of the ujikogari is evident from the reconstruction of Tsutsui Hachiman Shrine in {{ill|Bunka|ja|文化|1=Bunka|2=ja|3=文化 (元号)|4=de|5=Bunka (Ära)|6=ko|7=분카|12=draft|12=draft}} 13 (1816), which was funded by approximately 3,600 Kijishi from 36 provinces who were registered as ujiko.
